==English==

===Etymology===
Old English [[sceotan|scēotan]], from Germanic ''*skeutanan'', from Indo-European ''*(s)keud-''.  Cognate with Dutch [[schieten]], German [[schießen]], Swedish [[skjuta]]; and (''from Indo-European'') with Russian [[кидать]], Lithuanian [[skudrùs]].

===Pronunciation===
*{{SAMPA|/'Sut/}}
*{{IPA|/'ʃut/}}
*{{audio|en-us-shoot.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-uːt|-uːt]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|shoots|shooting|shot|'''[[shot]]''', or archaic '''[[shotten]]'''}}

# To [[fire]] a [[shot]].
# To [[fire]] more than one [[shot]].
# To [[hit]] with a [[shot]].
#:''He was '''shot''' by a police officer.''
# (''professional wrestling'') In professional wrestling, to deviate from [[kayfabe]], either intentionally or accidentally; to actually connect with unchoreographed fighting blows and manuevers, or speak one's mind (instead of an agreed-to script).

====Derived terms====
*[[shoot down]]
*[[shoot from the hip]]
*[[shoot onself in the foot]]

